Making some slight adjustments. The things that worry me most are not the “normal” causes of an inversion (i.e. Fed is tightening which raises the 2 year while buying in the 10 year and lower inflation expectations push that yield down)). Rather liquidity in the off-the-run market, algorithmic trading shocks, low dealer stock, volatility hedging, and trade unwinding which Could all cause an abnormal shift in the curve keeps me nervous. With that being said, the Fed has agreed to offer liquidity to ensure smooth funding and is buying Treasuries along the curve. That should be sufficient to keep it steep for the time-being. The real question becomes what happens when the short-rate is at the ZLB?

When will the yield curve for 2-year and 10-year U.S. Treasurys next invert? Hattip @ikresnak for a very complete well reasoned arguement which forces me to alter my forecast.

Yield curve inversions are predictive of recessions because investors think rates in the future will be lower than current rates and buy longer-dated bonds while selling shorter dated bonds. This is largely due to the fact that interest rates on the 10-yr reflect future expectations for inflation. If growth and inflation are expected to slow (a recession), then the 10-yr falls. Meanwhile, if the Fed is still hiking rates, the 2-yr rises and the curve inverts. Structural factors keeping inflation low have prevented this from occurring.
